<dl id="n53051s"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53051s">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53051s"> 51(s)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ce gros gar&ccedil;on g&acirc;tera tout. <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n53051s"><li>FW 54.22 </li><li><a href="../../flex/c/lexc.htm#n53051s">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/c/l39c.htm#n53051s">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n53051s">MS BL 47476b-173</ms> </li><li>JJA 49:367 <a name="cd10" href="../../ff/fdra/cda.htm#cd10">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/c/cd10.htm#n53051s">Draft: I.3&sect;1.10</a>/2.10/3.10</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Il &eacute;tait, du rest, tr&egrave;s bon pour les pauvres et d&eacute;clarait: <b>J&apos;aime mieux voir les courtisans rire de mon avarice, que le peuple pleurer de mes d&eacute;penses.</b> Son successeur ne l&apos;imita gu&egrave;re en cela. Louis XII avait dit de lui: <b>Ce gros gar&ccedil;on g&acirc;tera tout</b>. Fran&ccedil;ois Ier illustra cependant son r&egrave;gne par l&apos;amour des letters et des arts. <br><font color="green">[TABLE DES MOTS]</font> 106: Louis XII | <mark>Ce gros gar&ccedil;on g&acirc;tera tout.</mark> <small> E. Trogan, <a name="MHPF" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#MHPF"><cite title="source">Les Mots Historiques du Pays de France</cite></a> (1922) 32</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: &lsquo;This fat fellow will spoil everything&rsquo;: a remark made by Louis XII (1462-1515) regarding his son-in-law, the Ccmte d&apos;Angouleme (later Francis I), who was an incorrigible spendthrift. </mm> </dd></dl>
